  "prompt": "What should happen to our internet accounts, like Emails and Facebook, when we die?",
  "response": "Deciding what should happen to internet accounts after death is an important consideration in today\u2019s digital age. Here are some common approaches and considerations:\n\n1. **Digital Will**: Creating a digital will can specify your wishes regarding your online accounts. You can outline instructions for each account, whether they should be deleted, memorialized, or managed by someone else.\n\n2. **Account Planning Tools**: Many platforms now offer legacy or inactive account management tools:\n   - **Facebook** allows you to designate a \u201clegacy contact\u201d to manage your account or request memorialization after you pass away.\n   - **Google** offers the Inactive Account Manager, enabling you to decide what happens to your data after a period of inactivity.\n\n3. **Password Management**: Utilize a password manager to store all your login details. These managers often have features that allow you to pass on your digital keys to a trusted person.\n\n4. **Legal Considerations**: Depending on where you live, digital assets may be subject to different laws. It\u2019s advisable to consult with an attorney familiar with digital estate planning.\n\n5. **Family and Friends**: Communicate your wishes with trusted family members or friends. Make sure someone knows where to find your digital will or instructions.\n\n6. **Privacy and Security**: Consider the privacy implications of your accounts and data. Decide if you want some information to remain private even after death.\n\nBy taking these steps, you can ensure your digital presence is handled according to your wishes and that it does not become a burden for your loved ones.",
